Part 1: Data

The data set is comprised of 651 randomly sampled movies produced and released before 2016. random sampling indicates that this is an observational study; the information was collected from randomly sampled movies. Therefore, the sample size dealt in the below research question indicates that the study is generalizable to the population of interest (movies produced and released before 2016). On the other hand, since observational studies do not control any confounding variable, cause-and-effect conclusions between variables cannot be made based on the data.

Since the fact that independent random sampling was used to collect the data set and observations consist of fewer than 10% of the population ensures that the sample observations are independent. We can assume that the population distribution is not strongly skewed taking into a ccount the generalizability of the data mentioned above. Also, there are more than 30 independent observations. All these satisfied conditions allow us to use statistical inference when answering below research question.

However, since this data was gathered from the websites and platforms in which the official language is English, the data might only reflect the opinions of English-speaking people.

Part 2: Research question

The question is designed to study how audience score on Rotten Tomatoes (the variable ‘audience_score’) is related to relatively ‘intrinsic’ characteristics of movie such as, genre (the variable ‘genre’) and MPAA rating (the variable ‘mpaa_rating’), duration of movie (the variable ‘runtime’) and month it was released (the variable ‘thtr_rel_month’). Especially, I would like to see mpaa rating is a significant predictor of how audience scores a movie, given other intrinsic characteristics of movie variables (genre, runtime, and released month). This is because I am curious to explore that whether a sensational movie tends to have a better score due violent and sensational scenes.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

First and foremost, I decided to simplify several variables by combining 2-3 levels in those variables since some variables have too much levels in one variable or include some unnnecessary levels to answer the above research question.

I only considered the filiming style of “Feature Film” under the variable ‘title_type’ since movie types of Documentary and TV Movie are not likely to be shown in a typical movie theater. Thus, I dropped “Documentary” and “TV Movie” levels from the variable.

movies <- movies %>%
filter(title_type != "Documentary", title_type != "TV Movie") %>%
droplevels()

Second, I studied two explanatory variables (‘genre’ and ‘mpaa_rating’). I decided to simplify these variables by combining 2-3 related categories into 1 and dropping some categories.

Under the variable ‘genre’ there are 11 categories. Below table shows the genres of movies in descending order.

For simplification, I grouped several movie genre categories by creating a new variable called ‘genre_new’. Under this new variable, there are 6 levels instead of 11 levels. I merged the categories “Drama”, “Comedy” and “Documentary”, and “Horror” and “Mystery & Suspense”. Then, I merged “Mystery & Suspense” and “Horror”. Then, I dropped the ‘other’ level since I am only interested in specific genres to answer the research question. Also, I made a new variable with acronyms of genre to not over clutter data visualization: “Action & Adventure” with “A&A”, “Drama, Comedy and Documenary” with “DC&D”, “Art House & International” with “AH&I”, “Animation” with “Ani” and “Musical & Performing Arts” with “MPA”.

movies <- movies %>%
mutate(genre_new = ifelse(genre == "Action & Adventure","A&A",
ifelse(genre == "Horror", "H,M&S",
ifelse(genre == "Mystery & Suspense", "H,M&S",
ifelse(genre == "Science Fiction & Fantasy", "SFF", ifelse(genre == "Drama", "DC&D", ifelse(genre == "Art House & International", "AH&I", ifelse(genre == "Animation", "Ani", ifelse(genre == "Documentary", "DC&D", ifelse(genre == "Comedy", "DC&D", ifelse(genre == "Musical & Performing Arts", "MPA", NA)))))))))))

Since all explanatory variables are analyzed and their relationships with the response variable ‘audience_score’ are explored, now I would like to combine all these variables to determine the best model that predicts audience score on Rotten Tomatoes, and also to answer my above mentioned research question whether the mpaa rating of R tends to have higher audience score. * * *

Part 4: Modeling

As addressed in Part 2: Research Question section, I would like to consider how intrinsic characteristics of movie such as run time, mpaa rating, released month, and genre, contribute to the popularity of movie. Specifically, I would like to find out whether the mpaa rating variable is the strongest predictor variable in predicting audience score. Therefore, I excluded variables that are not ‘natural characteristics’ of movie such as whether a movie got an award, whether the movie, after released, was in the Top 200 Box office, or whether actor/actresses in that movie ever won an Oscar.

In order to separate other ‘non-natural’ characteristics of movie variables from ‘intrinsic’ characteristics of movie, in Part 3, I already made a data set ‘movies2’ which only includes the variables which show natural characteristics of movie.

Moreover, there are other rating variables that we could have considered as response variables such as, rating scores from IMDB and from Rotten Tomatoes critics. However, since those ratings could be colinear to one another, I only considered one rating variable, and I chose the audience score on Rotten Tomatoes which is broader.

I chose the p-value approach for the model selection since I would like to understand which variables are statistically significant predictors of the variable ‘audience_score’. I chose forward selection since we only have 4 predictor variables.

First, I added ‘genre_new’ variable. Below summary shows that ‘Drama, Comedy & Documentary’ genre and ‘Music & Performance Arts’ genre have the significance level less than \(\alpha\) = 0.05. Therefore, we include the variable ‘genre_new’.

movies_mlr1 = lm(audience_score ~ genre_new, data = movies2)

The final variable ‘runtime’ is added to our model. Since runtime has very small p-value, we include the variable into our model.

movies_mlr_final = lm(audience_score ~ genre_new + mpaa_new + runtime, data = movies2)

Thus, I selected the final model ‘movie_mlr_final’ which includes the variables that show genre, mpaa rating, and runtime.

This final formula shows a parsimonious model, the simplist model with the highest predictive power with 3 variables ‘genre_new’, ‘mpaa_new’ and ‘runtime’. Below ANOVA table further confirms the significance level of individual predictor variables. Unlike what I expected, runtime is the strongest predictor variable in this model. Mpaa rating is, on the other hand, the weakest predictor variable with p-value of 0.005.

anova(movies_mlr_final)
## Analysis of Variance Table

Now, I would like to run the model diagnostics. There are 4 assuptions that have to be considered when using the final model with multiple regression methods.

  1. each numerical variable is linearly related to the outcome. I checked this assuption by using residual plots to see whether numerical explanatory variable (in our model, only the variable ‘runtime’) is linearly related to the response variable ‘audience_score’. Below plot shows that dots are randomly scattered around 0. Most residuals are randomly clustered around run time of 80 minutes to 140 minutes. Therefore, this condition is met.
plot(lm(audience_score ~ runtime, data = movies2)$residuals ~ movies2$runtime)

  1. the residuals of the model are nearly normal I checked this assumption by using a histogram of residuals and a normal probability plot. If the residuals of the model are nearly normal, random scatter of residuals sould be around 0. There is a little bit of a skew in the residuals (right-skewed). However, it does not look like a serious right-skew. Also, the normal probability plot shows that except for the tail areas, we are not seeing the huge deviations from the mean 0. Thus, this condition is also met.
hist(movies_mlr_final$residuals)

qqnorm(movies_mlr_final$residuals)
qqline(movies_mlr_final$residuals)

  1. the variability of the residuals are nearly constant In order to see whether residuals are equally variable for low and high values of the predicted response variable, I checked using residual plots of residuals versus predicted value. The residual plot should not show any fan-shaped pattern. I also included absolute value of residuals versus predicted to detect unusual observations easily. It does not seem like the residual plot shows a fan-shaped pattern. Thus, this condition is also met.
plot(movies_mlr_final$residuals ~ movies_mlr_final$fitted)

plot(abs(movies_mlr_final$residuals) ~ movies_mlr_final$fitted)

  1. residuals are independent As discussed in Part 1, the data is collected by random sampling. Also, I checked by plotting the residuals which will appear in the order of data collection. The plot below does not show any patterns. Thus, the condition is also met.
plot(movies_mlr_final$residuals)

Part 5: Prediction

I selected “The Passangers”, a movie released in December 2016 by searching the Rotten Tomatoes website. The website gave me the information that its genre is “Action & Adventure”, its mpaa rating is “PG-13”, its runtime is 116 minutes, and its audience score is 63. With this information, I created a data case specific for this movie prediction.

audience_score <- 63
runtime <- 116
mpaa_new <- "PG-13"
genre_new <- "A&A"
Passangers <- data.frame (audience_score, runtime, mpaa_new, genre_new)

Then, I made a prediction of the movie “The Passangers” with the final model. The predicted audience score came out from the model was 52, which was 11 points lower than the actual audience score.

Prediction <- round(predict(movies_mlr_final, Passangers), digits = 0)
c(Prediction, Passangers$audience_score)
##  1    
## 52 63

We are 95% confident that, all else being equal, the predicted audience score for the movie “The Passangers” will be between 46.13 and 56.96. However, the model failed to predict the audience score of the movie “The Passangers” as the actual audience score is outside of 95% of confidence interval.

ci <- predict(movies_mlr_final, Passangers, interval = "confidence")
ci

Part 6: Conclusion

The final multiple regression model, set to explore which intrinsic characteristics of movie make a movie popular, shows that genre (‘genre_new’), mpaa rating (‘mpaa_new’), and duration of movie (‘runtime’) are statistically significant predictors of audience scores (audience_score). Released month of movies was not associated with audience score. Moreover, the variable ‘runtime’ was the most strongest predictor variable while the variable ‘mpaa rating’ was the weakest predictor variable, shown by the v-values explored in part 4.

However, as we saw in Part 5 that our model did not predict the audience score of a movie well. The data set “movies” contain more than 300 ‘Drama’ genre observations compared to other genres. Moreover, the number of mpaa rating of ‘R’ in the data set was significantly higher than the other mpaa ratings. These might have biased our model because the model would predict better a ‘drama’ movie or ‘R’ rated movie. However, at the same time, since audience score is subjective, I learned that we cannot just consider characteristics of movies but need to take into account individuality of audience.
